#X text 19 154 This is the same concept as pressing/releasing a note on your MIDI controller. In [envgen~] \, you just need to define a sustain point. Then \, the sustain stage depends on how long the gate is on. By the way \, the example below is exponential., f 49;
#X obj 849 425 *~;
#X obj 780 366 osc~ 440;
#X obj 849 467 out~;
#X obj 785 114 tgl 18 0 empty empty empty 17 7 0 10 #dcdcdc #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X obj 785 145 trigger float float;
#X obj 785 270 float;
#X obj 782 433 s2f~;
#X obj 782 463 vsl 18 100 0 1 0 0 empty empty empty 0 -9 0 10 #dcdcdc #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X obj 785 172 != 0;
#X obj 785 200 select 1 0;
#X msg 785 309 \$1 150;
#X obj 867 355 vline~;
#X msg 867 295 0 750;
#X obj 359 286 tgl 19 0 empty empty empty 0 -10 0 12 #dfdfdf #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X obj 161 287 envgen~ -suspoint 1 -curve 1 150 1 750 0, f 28;
#X text 82 476 Above we have an attack of 150 ms and a release of 750 ms. We have an exponential curve value of 1 \, (this is the same as the curvature setting of the [smooth~] object shown in the next example)., f 41;
#X text 19 93 An "ASR" ("Attack / Sustain / Release") envelope is usually controlled by a gate signal \, or on/off switch (like a toggle) to control the sustain period., f 49;
#X obj 222 53 declare -path else;
#X obj 471 197 function 200 100 empty empty 0 1 220 220 220 50 50 50 0 0 0 0 0 150 1 750 0;
#X obj 570 439 vsl 16 100 0 1 0 0 empty empty empty 0 -9 0 10 #dcdcdc #000000 #000000 0 1;
